overall_success_pre_1: Intention/Goal Success    When you consider the intentions or goals that you have for yourself, to what degree do you feel like you are successful in actually accomplishing those goals?     Please consider both big and small intentions or goals.    	100% success rate would mean that you are able to accomplish ALL of your goals/intentions. 	50% success rate would mean that you are able to accomplish about HALF of your goals/intentions. - Goal success rate (%)
global_day_actual_1: End of Day | Actual     Please estimate to what extent, on AVERAGE, you achieve your goals, intentions, tasks and responsibilities on a DAILY basis.    For example, at the END OF THE DAY when you think about all of the things you hoped to do that day, what percentage do you usually accomplish? - % success
global_day_belief_1: Beginning of Day | Belief     A similar question but... We want you to estimate what percentage of your goals you really, honestly believe you will accomplish each day. - % success belief

For example, one person may have a goal to cook their own dinner every night while you might not care at all whether you cook or eat out or order take out. debrief_form_1: University of Toronto, Scarborough  Debriefing Form   Principle Investigator: Cendri Hutcherson, Ph.D., Assistant Professor of PsychologProject Name: Tracking the gap between goals and outcomes in daily behavior Thank you for participating in our study!  We designed this study to better understand how people might experience a gap between their intentions and behavior, both at a day to day level, and at a broader life level. We hope to develop a better measurement of this gap that is reliable across contexts and across individuals.  Please understand that your participation in the research is voluntary and that you are free to withdraw your consent and data in the research at this time without any penalties. That is, you will receive full credit and payment for taking part in the study. Should you choose to withdraw from the study, all of the information that we obtained from your session will be destroyed. Thank you for your time and effort in our study. If you have any questions about the research, you may feel free and contact Dr. Cendri Hutcherson at c.hutcherson@utoronto.ca or (416) 208-4826. If you have any questions about your rights or treatment as a participant in this research project, please contact the University of Toronto’s Office of Research Ethics at ethics.review@utoronto.ca or (416) 946-3273. We also ask that you do not discuss this study with anyone outside of our research team, so that potential future participants will not be biased to behave in a certain way before participating in the study. Participant Consent By clicking below, you consent to give the principal investigator permission to use your data for this research project. - I consent for my data to be analyzed by the research team
